Problems 1-3 are based on the random variable \(X \sim \text{Binomial}(60, 0.4)\).

Problem 1

A

Calculate and report the mean and standard deviation of the distribution.

n = 60
p = 0.4
mean = n * p
stdev = sqrt(n * p * (1-p))
mean 
## [1] 24
stdev
## [1] 3.794733

-The mean of a binomial distribution of n = 60 and p = 0.4 is 24. The standard deviation would be about 3.795.

B

Calculate and report \(\mathsf{P}(X = 25)\)

dbinom(25, 60, 0.4)
## [1] 0.1004824

The probability of exactly 25 successes in a binomial distribution (60, 0.4) is around 10 percent.

C

Calculate and report \(\mathsf{P}(X >= 25)\)

1 - pbinom(25, 60, 0.4)
## [1] 0.343742

The probability of at least 25 successes in a binomial distribution (60, 0.4) is about 34.4 percent.

D

Create a graph which displays the binomial distribution with bars for \(x \ge 25\) colored in a different color from the rest to help visualize your answer to C.

gbinom(60, 0.4, scale=TRUE) +
  geom_binom_density(60, 0.4, a = NULL, b = NULL, color = "gray") +
  geom_binom_density(60, 0.4, a = 25, b = NULL, color = "red")

Problem 2

What is the probability that \(X\) is within one, two, and three standard deviations of the mean? Round each probability to four decimal places.

round(pbinom(mean + (c(1,2,3) * stdev), 60, 0.4) - pbinom(mean - (c(1,2,3) * stdev), 60, 0.4), 4)
## [1] 0.6436 0.9529 0.9978

Problem 3

Draw a graph of this binomial distribution with vertical lines with different line types at the end points of the intervals 1, 2, and 3 sigma from the mean.

  • solid for \(\mu \pm \sigma\)
  • dashed for \(\mu \pm 2\sigma\)
  • dotted for \(\mu \pm 3\sigma\)
gbinom(60, 0.4, scale=TRUE) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean + c(-1,1)*stdev,
             color = "red") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean + c(-2,2)*stdev,
             color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean + c(-3,3)*stdev,
             color = "red", linetype = "dotted")

Problem 4

A

Create a tibble where each row corresponds to a binomial distribution with the following columns:

  • n for \(n = 1000,1001, \ldots, 10,000\)
  • p equal to 0.9 for each row
  • mu equal to the mean
  • sigma equal to the standard deviation
  • q.975 equal to the 0.975 quantile of the distribution
  • z = (q.975 - mu)/sigma, the standardized z-score of the quantile
  • prob equal to \(\mathsf{P}(X \ge q.975)\), a right-tail probability for the distribution in each row

Display all columns and the rows of this table for which \(n\) is a multiple of 1000.

prob4 = tibble(
  n = seq(1000, 10000),
  p = 0.9,
  mu = n * p,
  sigma = sqrt(n * p * (1-p)),
  `q.975` = qbinom(0.975, n, p),
  z = (`q.975` - mu) / sigma,
  prob = 1 - pbinom(`q.975`, n, p)
)
prob4 %>%
  filter(n %% 1000 == 0)
## # A tibble: 10  7

B

Use a line plot to show the relationship between \(n\) on the x axis and \(z\) on the y axis. Add a smooth curve to highlight the trend. Describe the pattern you see.

prob4 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=n, y=z)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth()

Of binomial distributions with the same probability, it appears that the z-scores of the 97.5th percentile gradually increase as n increases, although the rate at which the z-scores increase is continually decreasing. Meaning, up to a point (around 5000 in this case) the distribution of z-scores follow a radical trend whereas past that point it is fairly linear and constant.

C

What is the average of the values of \(z\) for \(n > 9000\)?

prob4 %>%
  filter(n > 9000) %>%
  summarize(mean(z))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   `mean(z)`
##       <dbl>
## 1      1.95
